{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":2968926,"name":"Elliot Scher","username":"Gandagorn","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/gandagorn/{size}/267112_2.png","created_at":"2021-09-22T17:29:33.428Z","cooked":"<p>hello CD!!</p>
<p>I am programmer for team 2815 in Columbia SC and I am having some trouble with the SendableChooser. The way our code is written, we have multiple robotcontainers that house different commands and subsystems for whatever role we play in that match. The syntax for initializing a sendablechooser is</p>
<p>SendableChooser name = new SendableChooser&lt;&gt;();</p>
<p>Where V is the type of value to be stored.</p>
<p>I am not sure what to put for V when I want to use robotcontainers as my options</p>
<p>does anyone have any solutions?</p>
<p>is it even possible?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2021-09-22T17:43:20.381Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":42,"reads":87,"readers_count":86,"score":232.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":396111,"topic_slug":"sendablechooser-for-choosing-specific-robotcontainer","display_username":"Elliot Scher","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":49423,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"2815A (19-23) | 190M (23...)"},"post_url":"/t/sendablechooser-for-choosing-specific-robotcontainer/396111/1","custom_user_title":"2815A (19-23) | 190M (23...)","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":2968943,"name":"Allen Nuttle","username":"nuttle","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/nuttle/{size}/124105_2.png","created_at":"2021-09-22T19:00:03.071Z","cooked":"<p>Just to confirm, this looks like C++, based on the snips you’ve included?</p>
<p>Are your RobotContainers each a different class (and, if so, do they inherit from a common base class?) or, are your RobotContainers different instances of the same class?  The answer to your question depends on this.</p>
<p>The alternative approach is to have a single RobotContainer which includes all the different commands (the subsystems are typically not going to change).  The WPILib examples typically use a chooser to select from a set of commands for autonomous routines, so they show how to use a chooser to select different commands.  This might be a better overall approach.</p>
<p>The <code>&lt;type&gt;</code> syntax here is using a C++ feature called <a href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/templates-cpp/">templating</a>.  You can choose any type here.  For example, you could choose an enum and use that in a switch statement to change behaviors.  The examples tend to use a raw pointer to whatever class whose instance you are selecting (e.g. frc2::Command).  So, if all your RobotContainers are instances of the same class called “RobotContainer”, you could put “RobotContainer *” inside the <code>&lt;&gt;</code>.  If all your robot containers are different classes, you need for them to share a base class.  You would then put “MyRobotContainerBaseClass *” (or whatever name you used) inside the ‘&lt;&gt;’.  This is an example of <a href="https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/polymorphism-in-c/">polymorphism</a>.</p>
<p>This question really goes deeper than just the syntax to use, it’s really about the design.  The links on templating and polymorphism will probably be helpful, but only if you have a good handle on basic C++.  You can force just about any approach to work out, but things will be a lot cleaner and easier if you have a design which leverages features of the language.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2021-09-22T19:01:14.736Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":81,"readers_count":80,"score":26.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":396111,"topic_slug":"sendablechooser-for-choosing-specific-robotcontainer","display_username":"Allen Nuttle","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/polymorphism-in-c/","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Polymorphism in C++ - GeeksforGeeks","clicks":1},{"url":"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/templates-cpp/","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Templates in C++ - GeeksforGeeks","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":14283,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/sendablechooser-for-choosing-specific-robotcontainer/396111/2","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2968944,"name":"Elliot Scher","username":"Gandagorn","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/gandagorn/{size}/267112_2.png","created_at":"2021-09-22T19:03:46.937Z","cooked":"<p>Thanks for the Response! I am actually using Java but I think the principles are similar. How would you put all of the RobotContainers in the same base class? My robot containers are all in different classes because they use different hardware. For example, There is one robot container for all the PID control stuff and another for trajectory tracking. My mentor wants me to master all these concepts separately so I have a robot container for each one and I’d like to switch between them.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2021-09-22T19:07:53.403Z","reply_count":2,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":72,"readers_count":71,"score":29.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":396111,"topic_slug":"sendablechooser-for-choosing-specific-robotcontainer","display_username":"Elliot Scher","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":14283,"username":"nuttle","name":"Allen Nuttle","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/nuttle/{size}/124105_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":49423,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"2815A (19-23) | 190M (23...)"},"post_url":"/t/sendablechooser-for-choosing-specific-robotcontainer/396111/3","custom_user_title":"2815A (19-23) | 190M (23...)","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":2968947,"name":"Peter Johnson","username":"Peter_Johnson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/peter_johnson/{size}/10417_2.png","created_at":"2021-09-22T19:15:05.720Z","cooked":"<p>You need to have a common interface that both RobotContainers implement, e.g.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">public interface RobotContainerInterface {
  void doSomething();
}

public class RobotContainerA implements RobotContainerInterface {
  public void doSomething() {
     ...
  }
}

public class RobotContainerB implements RobotContainerInterface {
  public void doSomething() {
     ...
  }
}

SendableChooser&lt;RobotContainerInterface&gt; m_chooser = new SendableChooser&lt;&gt;();
m_chooser.setDefaultOption("A", new RobotContainerA());
m_chooser.addOption("B", new RobotContainerB());

RobotContainerInterface selected = chooser.getSelected();
if (selected != null) {
  selected.doSomething();
}
</code></pre>
<p>Note that in the above case both RobotContainer classes will be <em>constructed</em>… so you need to make sure they don’t use conflicting resources.  You can get around this by instead making the selected thing a function (lambda) that creates a RobotContainer:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">SendableChooser&lt;Supplier&lt;RobotContainerInterface&gt;&gt; m_chooser = new SendableChooser&lt;&gt;();
m_chooser.setDefaultOption("A", () -&gt; new RobotContainerA());
m_chooser.addOption("B", () -&gt; new RobotContainerB());

Supplier&lt;RobotContainerInterface&gt; supplier = chooser.getSelected();
if (supplier != null) {
  RobotContainerInterface container = supplier.get();
  container.doSomething();
}

</code></pre>
<p>The docs on SendableChooser will also be helpful:</p><aside class="onebox allowlistedgeneric">
